Decouple serializers from Devise modules. You can use any serializer at any time, as long the API required by the serializer is satisfied. Since session serializer is encrypted, it simply stores the id and the resource klass. Cookie is not encrypted, so it creates a random token and store it in the database, so in order to do the token cleanup, you need provide remember_me! and forget_me! methods, as in :rememberable.
Extract Activatable from Confirmable, so if you need to active your account through other means, you can still do so and ensure cherry pick works as expected.

Add an easy way to configure an application to sign in users through /sign_in.First, configure your routes:nn  map.devise_for :usersn  map.sign_in /sign_in, :controller => sessions, :action => newnnThen, in config/initializers/devise.rb:nn  config.use_default_scope = truennThe default scope is always the first declaration in routes.rb, but if you neednto change it, you can also do it through the initializer:nn  config.default_scope = :usern

Remove data_mapper support.Devise 1.1.0 will be released soon. This new version will support activerecord and mongoid as default ORMs. From now on, Devise will prefer ORM extensions as gems since this is the best way to handle dependencies.nnFor example, to allow Devise to work with Datamapper, it requires at least activemodel, dm-rails and dm-timestamps. If the ORM support comes from Devise gem, we cannot add dm-rails and dm-timestamps as dependencies, relying on the developer and documentation to find these out and install them.nnOther ORMs may still be added to Devise, as long as they are supported by the community, extend Devise test suite to have all tests passing and they necessarily use ActiveModel::Validations.n

Improve documentation on sending delayed emailsThere are a couple of gotchas in the existing documentationnabout the `send_devise_notification` hook.nn1.  The `after_commit` callback can be called multiple timesnso you should clear the array otherwise any additionalninvocations will trigger extra copies of the email.nn2.  The `after_commit` callback is only called when a recordnis created or updated so you need to check for `new_record?`nor `changed?` before adding it to `pending_notifications`notherwise it's okay to send it immediately.nnThe `new_record? || changed?` condition is necessary becausenthe latter isn't always true for new records, e.g:nn>> User.new.changed?n=> falsenn[ci skip]n

If we would only support Rails 4.2, this method could be somethingnlike this:nn```rubyndef with_devise_exclusive_scope(new_path, new_as, options)n  overrides = { as: new_as, path: new_path, module: nil }n  overrides.merge!(options.slice(:constraints, :defaults, :options))nn@scope = @scope.new(overrides)n  yieldnensuren  @scope = @scope.parentnendn```n

Allow warden proxy to change with request in testsThe warden method in the Devise::TestHelpers module adds a Warden proxynobject to the request environment hash under the 'warden' key. Includingnthis module in your test case registers that method as a callback, whichnruns before every test:nhttps://github.com/plataformatec/devise/blob/v3.4.1/lib/devise/test_helpers.rb#L12nnThe request object itself is created in a callback added by Rails:nhttps://github.com/rails/rails/blob/v4.2.0/actionpack/lib/action_controller/test_case.rb#L687nnSo before each test runs, the Rails callback creates the request object,nand then the Devise callback adds a Warden proxy object to it.nnI was using the rspec-retry gem (https://github.com/y310/rspec-retry),nand noticed that my controller specs would always fail whenever theynwere retried with this error:nnNoMethodError: undefined method `authenticate!' for nil:NilClassnnWhen rspec-retry re-runs a failed test, it runs the setup callbacksnagain. The Rails callback creates a new request object, but because ofnthe memoization that was here before, the Devise callback wouldn't add anWarden proxy to it, which was causing the error.nnWith this change, the Warden setup code will still only run once as longnas the request object stays the same, but if it changes a new Wardennproxy will be added to the new request object.n

Make `#increment_failed_attempts` concurrency safe (#4996)As reported in #4981, the method `#increment_failed_attempts` of `Devise::Models::Lockable` wasrnnot concurrency safe. The increment operation was being done in two steps: first the value was read from the database, and then incremented by 1. This may result in wrong values if two requests try to update the value concurrently. For example:rnrn```rnBrowser1 -------> Read `failed_attempts` from DB (1) -------> Increment `failed_attempts` to 2rnBrowser2 -------> Read `failed_attempts` from DB (1) -------> Increment `failed_attempts` to 2rn```rnrnIn the example above, `failed_attempts` should have been set to 3, but it will be set to 2. rnrnThis commit handles this case by calling `ActiveRecord::CounterCache.increment_counter` method, which will do both steps at once, reading the value straight from the database.rnrnThis commit also adds a `ActiveRecord::AttributeMethods::Dirty#reload` call to ensure that the application gets the updated value - i.e. that other request might have updated. rnAlthough this does not ensure that the value is in fact the most recent one - other request could've updated it after the `reload` call - it seems good enough for this implementation. rnEven if a request does not locks the account because it has a stale value, the next one - that updated that value - will do it. That's why we decided not to use a pessimistic lock here.rnrnCloses #4981.

Fix SQLite3 warningBefore setting this option, our test suite was giving the following warning:nn```nDEPRECATION WARNING: Leaving `ActiveRecord::ConnectionAdapters::SQLite3Adapter.represent_boolean_as_integer`nset to false is deprecated. SQLite databases have used 't' and 'f' to serializenboolean values and must have old data converted to 1 and 0 (its native booleannserialization) before setting this flag to true. Conversion can be accomplishednby setting up a rake task which runsnn  ExampleModel.where(boolean_column = 't').update_all(boolean_column: 1)n  ExampleModel.where(boolean_column = 'f').update_all(boolean_column: 0)nnfor all models and all boolean columns, after which the flag must be set tontrue by adding the following to your application.rb file:nn  Rails.application.config.active_record.sqlite3.represent_boolean_as_integer = truen (called from <top (required)> at $PATH/devise/test/rails_app/app/active_record/user.rb:5)n```nnAfter configuring `represent_boolean_as_integer = true` as specifiednabove, we don't have this warning anymore.nnMore info:nhttps://api.rubyonrails.org/classes/ActiveRecord/ConnectionAdapters/SQLite3Adapter.html#method-c-represent_boolean_as_integern
